{"title_page": "Just a Gigolo (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = [[Song]]\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| language   = [[German language|German]]\n| written    =\n| published  = [[1929]], in [[Vienna]]\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[tango]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Leonello Casucci]] (in [[1928]])\n| lyricist   = [[Julius Brammer]] ([[1924]], in German)<br />[[Irving Caesar]] ([[1929]], in English)\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n[[File:Just a Gigolo (1932).webm|thumb|thumbtime=216|start=214|end=429|[[Ir\u00e8ne Bordoni]] (1932)]]\n\"'''Just a Gigolo'''\" is a popular song, adapted by [[Irving Caesar]] into English in 1929 from the [[Austria]]n tango \"'''Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo'''\", composed in 1928 in Vienna by [[Leonello Casucci]] to lyrics written in 1924 by [[Julius Brammer]].<ref name=\"Petrescu2007\">{{cite book|author=Mihaela Petrescu|title=Vamps, Eintaenzer, and Desperate Housewives: Social Dance in Weimar Literature and Film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgnw9kdMNScC&pg=PA9|year=2007|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-44284-4|pages=9\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Jazz-Standards. Das Lexikon. 3. Auflage. | publisher=B\u00e4renreiter | author=Schaal, Hans-J\u00fcrgen | year=2004 | location=Kassel |page=269 |language=German| isbn=9783761814147}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe song was first published by Wiener Boheme Verlag in 1929 and performed by several orchestras in Germany that year, including [[Dajos B\u00e9la]]'s orchestra with the singer Kurt M\u00fchlhardt. In Italy [[Daniele Serra]] sang a version entitled \"Gigolo\", followed by Sirio Di Piramo and his orchestra in 1930, while other countries provided their own versions.<ref>{{cite book | title=Il jazz in Italia: dalle origini alle grandi orchestre | author=Mazzoletti, Adriano | year=1983 |location=Rome|page=92 |language=Italian| isbn=88-7063-704-2}}</ref>\n\nThe original version is a poetic vision of the social collapse experienced in [[Austria]] after [[World War I]], represented by the figure of a former [[hussar]] who remembers himself parading in his uniform, while now he has to get by as a lonely hired dancer. The music features a simple melodic sequence, but nonetheless has a clever harmonic construction that highlights the mixed emotions in the lyrics, adding a nostalgic, bittersweet effect.\n\nThe success of the song prompted publishers [[Chappell & Co.]] to buy the rights and order an [[English language|English]] version from Irving Caesar, a very popular lyricist of the time. Caesar eliminated the specific Austrian references and, in the often-omitted verse (but included in the 1931 recording by [[Bing Crosby]]), set the action in a [[Paris]] cafe, where a local character tells his sad story. Thus, the lyrics retained their sentimental side but lost their historic value. Popular versions in 1931 were by [[Ted Lewis (musician)|Ted Lewis]], [[Ben Bernie]], Bing Crosby and [[Leo Reisman]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/534 534]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/534}}</ref>\n\n\"Just a Gigolo\" appeared in a 1931 film, a 1932 [[Betty Boop]] cartoon and a 1993 TV series, all titled after the song. The song was recorded by many musicians of the time, including [[Louis Armstrong]] and (in [[German language|German]]) [[Richard Tauber]].\n\nThe film ''[[Just a Gigolo (1978 film)|Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo]]'', directed by [[David Hemmings]] in 1979, was titled after the first verse of the original lyrics, but the ''Just a Gigolo'' title was used for [[United States of America|US]] distribution. In this film, the song was performed by [[Marlene Dietrich]], in her last film appearance.\n\n==\"Just a Gigolo\"/\"I Ain't Got Nobody\" medley==\n\n===Origin===\n\"Just a Gigolo\" is best known in a form recorded by [[Louis Prima]] in 1956, where it was paired in a medley with another old standard, \"[[I Ain't Got Nobody]]\" (words by [[Roger A. Graham]] and music by [[Spencer Williams]], 1915). This pairing links the life of a gigolo (\"people know the part I'm playing, paid for every dance..\"), to the outcome for singer ending up alone (\"I ain't got nobody\"). The popularity of Prima's combination, and of [[Village People]]'s 1978 and [[David Lee Roth]]'s 1985 cover versions of the medley, has led to the mistaken perception by some that the songs are two parts of a single original composition.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\nThe coupling of the two songs had its genesis in an earlier Louis Prima recording from 1945 (V Disc 554, side A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Louis-Prima-And-His-Orchestra-Lt-Bob-Crosby-USMC-And-His-V-Disc-Bob-Cats--Just-A-Gigolo-Its-A-Long-W/release/6344864 |title=Louis Prima And His Orchestra / Lt Bob Crosby (USMC) And His V-Disc Bob Cats /* - Just A Gigolo / It's A Long Way To Tipperary (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date=1945-05-17 |accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>), which was then adapted  by [[Sam Butera]] for Prima's 1950s Las Vegas stage show, during which Prima would revisit his old hits in a new, jive-and-jumping style. The success of that act gained Prima a recording deal with [[Capitol Records]], which aimed to capture on record the atmosphere of his shows. The first album, titled ''[[The Wildest!]]'' and released in November 1956,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Reviews and Ratings of New Albums |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|The Billboard]] |date=17 November 1956 |page=26 |issn=0006-2510 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fgoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26 |accessdate=11 January 2012 }}</ref> opened with \"Just a Gigolo\"/\"I Ain't Got Nobody\", which then became Prima's signature number and helped relaunch his career.\n\n===Louis Prima's recording===\nThe recording session took place in April 1956 at [[Capitol Tower]] Studios, [[Los Angeles]], and was produced by [[Voyle Gilmore]]. Prima was backed by his Las Vegas group, [[Sam Butera]] & the Witnesses, in its original line-up: Sam Butera ([[tenor saxophone|tenor sax]]), James \"Red\" Blount ([[trombone]]), William \"Willie\" McCumber ([[piano]]), [[Jack Marshall (composer)|Jack Marshall]] ([[guitar]]), Amado Rodriques ([[Double bass|bass]]) and Robert \"Bobby\" Morris ([[Drum kit|drums]]). [[Keely Smith]], who was Prima's wife and an important part of his act, joined the Witnesses for the characteristic backing vocals. Prima sang the lead but didn't play the trumpet on this track.\n\n==List of versions==\nThe following artists have released or performed versions of the song:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?esongId=105944700 |title=Just a Gigolo |work=Song Search |publisher=Warner Chappell Music |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113182230/http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?esongId=105944700 |archivedate=2007-11-13 }}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Marie-Louise Damien|Damia]] (1931) as \"C'est mon Gigolo\" (French version adapted from L. Casucci by A. Mauprey, J. Lenoir)\n* [[Fats Waller]]\n* [[Django Reinhardt]] and [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]] in Rome (1949)\n* [[Art Tatum]]\n* [[Sol Ho\u02bbopi\u02bbi]] (1928)\n* [[Louis Armstrong]]  March 9 (1931)\n* [[Ted Lewis (musician)|Ted Lewis]] and His Band (Columbia 2378 D) (1931)\n* [[Ben Bernie]] and His Orchestra (Brunswick 6023) (1931)\n* [[Bing Crosby]] with The [[Gus Arnheim]] Orchestra (recorded March 2, 1931)<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/crosby1a.html|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>  &ndash; includes Paris verse.\n* [[Leo Reisman]] and His Orchestra (Victor 22606) (1931)\n* [[Jaye P. Morgan]] (1953) - a minor hit, reaching No. 22 in the Billboard charts.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/322 322]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/322}}</ref>\n* [[Harry James]] (1952)\n* [[Louis Prima]] (1956)\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] - included in the album ''[[At Mister Kelly's]]'' (1957)\n* Eino Virtanen, a Finnish version called \"Kaunis Gigolo\" (1958)\n* [[Thelonious Monk]] (1954, 1958, 1962)\n* [[Gus Backus]]\n* [[Carmen McRae]] - included in her album ''Song Time'' (1960).<ref>{{cite web|title=allmusic.com|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/song-time-mw0000120232|website=allmusic.com|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jean Shepherd]] (1965) opened the July 29, 1965 episode of his show with the song\n* [[Erroll Garner]] (1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?menu_status=songsearch&esongId=125925000 |title=Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo |work=Song Search |publisher=Warner Chappell Music }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Connie Francis]] - for the album ''[[Connie & Clyde \u2013 Hit Songs of the 30s]]'' (1968)\n* [[Oscar Peterson]] (1970)\n* [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] (1974)\n* [[Chris DeMarco as Michel Delon]] (1976)\n* Prima's version was covered by [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]] in 1979 on his ''[[The Mafia Stole My Guitar]]'' album.\n* [[Village People]] (1978) recorded a cover of Prima's version.\n* [[Marlene Dietrich]] title song of film ''[[Just a Gigolo (1978 film)|Just a Gigolo]]'' (1978)\n* [[Barbie and the Kens]] (1980)\n* Javier Gurruchaga during the film ''Besame Tonta'' (1981)\n* [[Bob Rivers|Bob (Rivers)]] & Zip (1985), with alternate lyrics \"Just a Big Ego\"\n* [[David Lee Roth]] (1985) (reached #12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]).  The music video for his recording parodies a number of well-known pop-music performers [[Michael Jackson]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Billy Idol]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Culture Club]], cameos appearances and cultural trends of the first half of the 1980s.\n* [[Tiny Tim (musician)|Tiny Tim]] (1987) on the record \"[[Tiptoe Through the Tulips]]\"\n* [[Tony Martin (entertainer)|Tony Martin]] (1985)\n* Tapani Kansa, a Finnish version called \"Vastustamaton\" on his album ''Anna mulle aikaa'' (1990)\n* [[Marty Grosz]] (1992, 2005)\n* [[Leningrad Cowboys]] (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leningradcowboys.fi/main.site?action%3Dsiteupdate%2Fview%26id%3D13 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 5, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061011173459/http://www.leningradcowboys.fi/main.site?action=siteupdate%2Fview&id=13 |archivedate=October 11, 2006 }}</ref>\n* [[Tony Slattery]] (1993) as the closing song for the TV show \"[[Just a Gigolo (TV series)|Just a Gigolo]]\" in which he also stars.\n* [[Amanda Lear]] utilizes the song in her live repertoire and a 1998 recording can found on the compilation ''Made of Blood and Honey'' (reportedly a #1 hit in Hungary, Romania, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Andorra{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}).\n* [[Dick Hyman]] Group and [[Howard Alden]] (1999) in [[Woody Allen]]'s [[Sweet and Lowdown]]\n* [[Lou Bega]] (2001)\n* In 2003 [[Israelis|Israeli]] singer and TV star, [[Gidi Gov]], released a [[Hebrew]] version of the song, called \"Gigolo\" on his album ''Moondance'' (Hebrew: \u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d5\u05d3 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d7).\n* The [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] [[Marching Illini]] are also well known for performing the song as part of their post-game show.\n* [[Swedish people|Swedish]] [[dansband]] [[Ingmar Nordstr\u00f6ms]] recorded a Swedish-language version of the song, called \"G\u00f6sta Gigolo\", on the 1985 album ''Saxparty 12''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smdb.kb.se/catalog/id/001890300|title=Saxparty 12|publisher=Svensk mediedatabas|language=Swedish|date=1985|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> The title is pronounced the same as in English, but refers to a man named G\u00f6sta and is hanging around the dance floor in the hotel of a small town.\n* Sergio P\u00e1ngaro & Baccarat (Spanish version, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.com.ar/discos/3/3053.shtml |title=Baccarat en castellano, un disco de Baccarat |website=Rock.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>\n* [[Tyler Lewis]] (2006)\n* In 2007 [[Paolo Belli]] released \"''Io Sono Un Gigol\u00f2''\", an Italian version of the song.\n* [[Lucio Dalla]] and [[Francesco De Gregori]], with new Italian text, on their 2010 live album ''Work in Progress''.\n* [[Mina (Italian singer)]] recorded and released the song on her 2012 album ''[[12 (American Song Book)]]''.\n* [[The Jive Aces]] on the ''King of the Swingers'' album (A Salute to [[Louis Prima]]).\n* [[Frank D'Angelo]] recorded and released the song on his 2015 album I Want to Live Forever: Official Soundtrack from the Feature Film [[Sicilian Vampire]].\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The song is sung in [[Floyd Gottfredson]]'s [[Mickey Mouse (comic strip)|''Mickey Mouse'' comic strip]] first published May 14, 1931 (part of a story called \"High Society\").\n* The song's lyrics are parodied in an original ''[[Star Trek]]'' novel, ''[[How Much for Just the Planet?]]'' (1987) by [[John M. Ford]].\n* On his 1962 album, ''[[Oh Yeah (Charles Mingus album)|Oh Yeah]]'', a piano-playing [[Charles Mingus]] repeatedly sings the first line of the song in his own composition, \"Devil Woman\".\n*The song is briefly sung in [[Edward Albee]]'s ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'' by the character Martha.\n*The song is played in the Salon Kitty scenes of the 1981 BBC television miniseries ''[[Private Schulz]]''.\n* The Crosby version of the song plays during the final scene and credits of ''[[Mad Men]]'' season 6/episode 3: \"[[The Collaborators (Mad Men)|The Collaborators]]\".\n* The song is being played on a piano during the Zeppelin scene in the film ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]'' while two characters are talking about a woman.\n* The Prima version of the song can be heard in the trailer for the 2013 [[John Turturro]] film, ''[[Fading Gigolo]]''.\n* The Prima version of the song is featured in the 2013 rhythm game ''[[Just Dance 2014]]'' for Nintendo Wii, Wii U, PS3, PS4, Xbox 360 and Xbox One. It also has an unlockable mashup that can be bought with mojo that features dancers from Funkytown, Forget You, Boomsday, and more.\n* The Prima version is also sung by [[Robert De Niro]] in ''[[Mad Dog and Glory]]'' (1993).\n* The video for David Lee Roth's version is featured on the ''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]'' episode \"Eating Contest\" (1993).\n* A line of David Lee Roth's version is heard during the song \"Goofy Goober Rock\" in ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' (2004).\n* The Prima version was featured Fox animated series ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Looking for Mr. Goodbart]]\".\n* The song was used by the well-known YouTube channel Greenboys for their video \"Yoda Sings\".\n* The Prima version was referenced in the Mel Brooks film \"Young Frankenstein.\" Igor sings the song briefly while pretending to be a disembodied head.\n* The song was also covered for the opening credits for 2014 film, ''[[Bad Grandpa]]''\n*The Bing Crosby version is used as the closing song of episode 3 of the 6th season of Mad Men.\n* The song was used extensively in the 2015 Frank D'Angelo classic \"[[Sicilian Vampire]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-lee-roth|just-a-gigolo}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Jaye P. Morgan}}\n{{Lou Bega}}\n{{Bing Crosby}}\n{{Louis Prima}}\n\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Village People songs]]\n[[Category:David Lee Roth songs]]\n[[Category:Lou Bega songs]]\n[[Category:Amanda Lear songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Irving Caesar]]\n[[Category:1929 songs]]\n[[Category:Ingmar Nordstr\u00f6ms songs]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Marlene Dietrich songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = [[Song]]\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| language   = [[German language|German]]\n| written    =\n| published  = [[1929]], in [[Vienna]]\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[tango]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Leonello Casucci]] (in [[1928]])\n| lyricist   = [[Julius Brammer]] ([[1924]], in German)<br />[[Irving Caesar]] ([[1929]], in English)\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n[[File:Just a Gigolo (1932).webm|thumb|thumbtime=216|start=214|end=429|[[Ir\u00e8ne Bordoni]] (1932)]]\n\"'''Just a Gigolo'''\" is a popular song, adapted by [[Irving Caesar]] into English in 1929 from the [[Austria]]n tango \"'''Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo'''\", composed in 1928 in Vienna by [[Leonello Casucci]] to lyrics written in 1924 by [[Julius Brammer]].<ref name=\"Petrescu2007\">{{cite book|author=Mihaela Petrescu|title=Vamps, Eintaenzer, and Desperate Housewives: Social Dance in Weimar Literature and Film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wgnw9kdMNScC&pg=PA9|year=2007|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-44284-4|pages=9\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Jazz-Standards. Das Lexikon. 3. Auflage. | publisher=B\u00e4renreiter | author=Schaal, Hans-J\u00fcrgen | year=2004 | location=Kassel |page=269 |language=German| isbn=9783761814147}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe song was first published by Wiener Boheme Verlag in 1929 and performed by several orchestras in Germany that year, including [[Dajos B\u00e9la]]'s orchestra with the singer Kurt M\u00fchlhardt. In Italy [[Daniele Serra]] sang a version entitled \"Gigolo\", followed by Sirio Di Piramo and his orchestra in 1930, while other countries provided their own versions.<ref>{{cite book | title=Il jazz in Italia: dalle origini alle grandi orchestre | author=Mazzoletti, Adriano | year=1983 |location=Rome|page=92 |language=Italian| isbn=88-7063-704-2}}</ref>\n\nThe original version is a poetic vision of the social collapse experienced in [[Austria]] after [[World War I]], represented by the figure of a former [[hussar]] who remembers himself parading in his uniform, while now he has to get by as a lonely hired dancer. The music features a simple melodic sequence, but nonetheless has a clever harmonic construction that highlights the mixed emotions in the lyrics, adding a nostalgic, bittersweet effect.\n\nThe success of the song prompted publishers [[Chappell & Co.]] to buy the rights and order an [[English language|English]] version from Irving Caesar, a very popular lyricist of the time. Caesar eliminated the specific Austrian references and, in the often-omitted verse (but included in the 1931 recording by [[Bing Crosby]]), set the action in a [[Paris]] cafe, where a local character tells his sad story. Thus, the lyrics retained their sentimental side but lost their historic value. Popular versions in 1931 were by [[Ted Lewis (musician)|Ted Lewis]], [[Ben Bernie]], Bing Crosby and [[Leo Reisman]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/534 534]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/534}}</ref>\n\n\"Just a Gigolo\" appeared in a 1931 film, a 1932 [[Betty Boop]] cartoon and a 1993 TV series, all titled after the song. The song was recorded by many musicians of the time, including [[Louis Armstrong]] and (in [[German language|German]]) [[Richard Tauber]].\n\nThe film ''[[Just a Gigolo (1978 film)|Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo, armer Gigolo]]'', directed by [[David Hemmings]] in 1979, was titled after the first verse of the original lyrics, but the ''Just a Gigolo'' title was used for [[United States of America|US]] distribution. In this film, the song was performed by [[Marlene Dietrich]], in her last film appearance.\n\n==\"Just a Gigolo\"/\"I Ain't Got Nobody\" medley==\n\n===Origin===\n\"Just a Gigolo\" is best known in a form recorded by [[Louis Prima]] in 1956, where it was paired in a medley with another old standard, \"[[I Ain't Got Nobody]]\" (words by [[Roger A. Graham]] and music by [[Spencer Williams]], 1915). This pairing links the life of a gigolo (\"people know the part I'm playing, paid for every dance..\"), to the outcome for singer ending up alone (\"I ain't got nobody\"). The popularity of Prima's combination, and of [[Village People]]'s 1978 and [[David Lee Roth]]'s 1985 cover versions of the medley, has led to the mistaken perception by some that the songs are two parts of a single original composition.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}\n\nThe coupling of the two songs had its genesis in an earlier Louis Prima recording from 1945 (V Disc 554, side A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Louis-Prima-And-His-Orchestra-Lt-Bob-Crosby-USMC-And-His-V-Disc-Bob-Cats--Just-A-Gigolo-Its-A-Long-W/release/6344864 |title=Louis Prima And His Orchestra / Lt Bob Crosby (USMC) And His V-Disc Bob Cats /* - Just A Gigolo / It's A Long Way To Tipperary (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date=1945-05-17 |accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>), which was then adapted  by [[Sam Butera]] for Prima's 1950s Las Vegas stage show, during which Prima would revisit his old hits in a new, jive-and-jumping style. The success of that act gained Prima a recording deal with [[Capitol Records]], which aimed to capture on record the atmosphere of his shows. The first album, titled ''[[The Wildest!]]'' and released in November 1956,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Reviews and Ratings of New Albums |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|The Billboard]] |date=17 November 1956 |page=26 |issn=0006-2510 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fgoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26 |accessdate=11 January 2012 }}</ref> opened with \"Just a Gigolo\"/\"I Ain't Got Nobody\", which then became Prima's signature number and helped relaunch his career.\n\n===Louis Prima's recording===\nThe recording session took place in April 1956 at [[Capitol Tower]] Studios, [[Los Angeles]], and was produced by [[Voyle Gilmore]]. Prima was backed by his Las Vegas group, [[Sam Butera]] & the Witnesses, in its original line-up: Sam Butera ([[tenor saxophone|tenor sax]]), James \"Red\" Blount ([[trombone]]), William \"Willie\" McCumber ([[piano]]), [[Jack Marshall (composer)|Jack Marshall]] ([[guitar]]), Amado Rodriques ([[Double bass|bass]]) and Robert \"Bobby\" Morris ([[Drum kit|drums]]). [[Keely Smith]], who was Prima's wife and an important part of his act, joined the Witnesses for the characteristic backing vocals. Prima sang the lead but didn't play the trumpet on this track.\n\n==List of versions==\nThe following artists have released or performed versions of the song:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?esongId=105944700 |title=Just a Gigolo |work=Song Search |publisher=Warner Chappell Music |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113182230/http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?esongId=105944700 |archivedate=2007-11-13 }}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Marie-Louise Damien|Damia]] (1931) as \"C'est mon Gigolo\" (French version adapted from L. Casucci by A. Mauprey, J. Lenoir)\n* [[Fats Waller]]\n* [[Django Reinhardt]] and [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]] in Rome (1949)\n* [[Art Tatum]]\n* [[Sol Ho\u02bbopi\u02bbi]] (1928)\n* [[Louis Armstrong]]  March 9 (1931)\n* [[Ted Lewis (musician)|Ted Lewis]] and His Band (Columbia 2378 D) (1931)\n* [[Ben Bernie]] and His Orchestra (Brunswick 6023) (1931)\n* [[Bing Crosby]] with The [[Gus Arnheim]] Orchestra (recorded March 2, 1931)<ref>{{cite web|title=A Bing Crosby Discography|url=http://www.bingmagazine.co.uk/bingmagazine/crosby1a.html|website=BING magazine|publisher=International Club Crosby|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>  &ndash; includes Paris verse.\n* [[Leo Reisman]] and His Orchestra (Victor 22606) (1931)\n* [[Jaye P. Morgan]] (1953) - a minor hit, reaching No. 22 in the Billboard charts.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitburn|first1=Joel|title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954|date=1986|publisher=Record Research Inc|location=Wisconsin, USA|isbn=0-89820-083-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/322 322]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwpopmemories00whit/page/322}}</ref>\n* [[Harry James]] (1952)\n* [[Louis Prima]] (1956)\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] - included in the album ''[[At Mister Kelly's]]'' (1957)\n* Eino Virtanen, a Finnish version called \"Kaunis Gigolo\" (1958)\n* [[Thelonious Monk]] (1954, 1958, 1962)\n* [[Gus Backus]]\n* [[Carmen McRae]] - included in her album ''Song Time'' (1960).<ref>{{cite web|title=allmusic.com|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/song-time-mw0000120232|website=allmusic.com|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jean Shepherd]] (1965) opened the July 29, 1965 episode of his show with the song\n* [[Erroll Garner]] (1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warnerchappell.com/wcm_2/song_search/song_detail/songview_2.jsp?menu_status=songsearch&esongId=125925000 |title=Sch\u00f6ner Gigolo |work=Song Search |publisher=Warner Chappell Music }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Connie Francis]] - for the album ''[[Connie & Clyde \u2013 Hit Songs of the 30s]]'' (1968)\n* [[Oscar Peterson]] (1970)\n* [[Peter Allen (musician)|Peter Allen]] (1974)\n* [[Chris DeMarco as Michel Delon]] (1976)\n* Prima's version was covered by [[Alex Harvey (musician)|Alex Harvey]] in 1979 on his ''[[The Mafia Stole My Guitar]]'' album.\n* [[Village People]] (1978) recorded a cover of Prima's version.\n* [[Marlene Dietrich]] title song of film ''[[Just a Gigolo (1978 film)|Just a Gigolo]]'' (1978)\n* [[Barbie and the Kens]] (1980)\n* Javier Gurruchaga during the film ''Besame Tonta'' (1981)\n* [[Bob Rivers|Bob (Rivers)]] & Zip (1985), with alternate lyrics \"Just a Big Ego\"\n* [[David Lee Roth]] (1985) (reached #12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]).  The music video for his recording parodies a number of well-known pop-music performers [[Michael Jackson]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Billy Idol]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Culture Club]], cameos appearances and cultural trends of the first half of the 1980s.\n* [[Tiny Tim (musician)|Tiny Tim]] (1987) on the record \"[[Tiptoe Through the Tulips]]\"\n* [[Tony Martin (entertainer)|Tony Martin]] (1985)\n* Tapani Kansa, a Finnish version called \"Vastustamaton\" on his album ''Anna mulle aikaa'' (1990)\n* [[Marty Grosz]] (1992, 2005)\n* [[Leningrad Cowboys]] (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leningradcowboys.fi/main.site?action%3Dsiteupdate%2Fview%26id%3D13 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 5, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061011173459/http://www.leningradcowboys.fi/main.site?action=siteupdate%2Fview&id=13 |archivedate=October 11, 2006 }}</ref>\n* [[Tony Slattery]] (1993) as the closing song for the TV show \"[[Just a Gigolo (TV series)|Just a Gigolo]]\" in which he also stars.\n* [[Amanda Lear]] utilizes the song in her live repertoire and a 1998 recording can found on the compilation ''Made of Blood and Honey'' (reportedly a #1 hit in Hungary, Romania, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Andorra{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}).\n* [[Dick Hyman]] Group and [[Howard Alden]] (1999) in [[Woody Allen]]'s [[Sweet and Lowdown]]\n* [[Lou Bega]] (2001)\n* In 2003 [[Israelis|Israeli]] singer and TV star, [[Gidi Gov]], released a [[Hebrew]] version of the song, called \"Gigolo\" on his album ''Moondance'' (Hebrew: \u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d5\u05d3 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d7).\n* The [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] [[Marching Illini]] are also well known for performing the song as part of their post-game show.\n* [[Swedish people|Swedish]] [[dansband]] [[Ingmar Nordstr\u00f6ms]] recorded a Swedish-language version of the song, called \"G\u00f6sta Gigolo\", on the 1985 album ''Saxparty 12''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smdb.kb.se/catalog/id/001890300|title=Saxparty 12|publisher=Svensk mediedatabas|language=Swedish|date=1985|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> The title is pronounced the same as in English, but refers to a man named G\u00f6sta and is hanging around the dance floor in the hotel of a small town.\n* Sergio P\u00e1ngaro & Baccarat (Spanish version, 2003)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rock.com.ar/discos/3/3053.shtml |title=Baccarat en castellano, un disco de Baccarat |website=Rock.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2016-06-14}}</ref>\n* [[Tyler Lewis]] (2006)\n* In 2007 [[Paolo Belli]] released \"''Io Sono Un Gigol\u00f2''\", an Italian version of the song.\n* [[Lucio Dalla]] and [[Francesco De Gregori]], with new Italian text, on their 2010 live album ''Work in Progress''.\n* [[Mina (Italian singer)]] recorded and released the song on her 2012 album ''[[12 (American Song Book)]]''.\n* [[The Jive Aces]] on the ''King of the Swingers'' album (A Salute to [[Louis Prima]]).\n* [[Frank D'Angelo]] recorded and released the song on his 2015 album I Want to Live Forever: Official Soundtrack from the Feature Film [[Sicilian Vampire]].\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The song is sung in [[Floyd Gottfredson]]'s [[Mickey Mouse (comic strip)|''Mickey Mouse'' comic strip]] first published May 14, 1931 (part of a story called \"High Society\").\n* The song's lyrics are parodied in an original ''[[Star Trek]]'' novel, ''[[How Much for Just the Planet?]]'' (1987) by [[John M. Ford]].\n* On his 1962 album, ''[[Oh Yeah (Charles Mingus album)|Oh Yeah]]'', a piano-playing [[Charles Mingus]] repeatedly sings the first line of the song in his own composition, \"Devil Woman\".\n*The song is briefly sung in [[Edward Albee]]'s ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]'' by the character Martha.\n*The song is played in the Salon Kitty scenes of the 1981 BBC television miniseries ''[[Private Schulz]]''.\n* The Crosby version of the song plays during the final scene and credits of ''[[Mad Men]]'' season 6/episode 3: \"[[The Collaborators (Mad Men)|The Collaborators]]\".\n* The song is being played on a piano during the Zeppelin scene in the film ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]'' while two characters are talking about a woman.\n* The Prima version of the song can be heard in the trailer for the 2013 [[John Turturro]] film, ''[[Fading Gigolo]]''.\n* The Prima version of the song is featured in the 2013 rhythm game ''[[Just Dance 2014]]'' for Nintendo Wii, Wii U, PS3, PS4, Xbox 360 and Xbox One.\n* The Prima version is also sung by [[Robert De Niro]] in ''[[Mad Dog and Glory]]'' (1993).\n* The video for David Lee Roth's version is featured on the ''[[Beavis and Butt-Head]]'' episode \"Eating Contest\" (1993).\n* A line of David Lee Roth's version is heard during the song \"Goofy Goober Rock\" in ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' (2004).\n* The Prima version was featured Fox animated series ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Looking for Mr. Goodbart]]\".\n* The song was used by the well-known YouTube channel Greenboys for their video \"Yoda Sings\".\n* The Prima version was referenced in the Mel Brooks film \"Young Frankenstein.\" Igor sings the song briefly while pretending to be a disembodied head.\n* The song was also covered for the opening credits for 2014 film, ''[[Bad Grandpa]]''\n*The Bing Crosby version is used as the closing song of episode 3 of the 6th season of Mad Men.\n* The song was used extensively in the 2015 Frank D'Angelo classic \"[[Sicilian Vampire]]\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-lee-roth|just-a-gigolo}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Jaye P. Morgan}}\n{{Lou Bega}}\n{{Bing Crosby}}\n{{Louis Prima}}\n\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:2001 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Village People songs]]\n[[Category:David Lee Roth songs]]\n[[Category:Lou Bega songs]]\n[[Category:Amanda Lear songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Irving Caesar]]\n[[Category:1929 songs]]\n[[Category:Ingmar Nordstr\u00f6ms songs]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Marlene Dietrich songs]]\n", "name_user": "32.212.236.33", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn popular culture)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Just_a_Gigolo_(song)"}
